---SECURITY INCIDENT REPORT---

Incident ID: 316
Reported By: Braulio Garcia - Tier 1 SOC Analyst 
Date: February 26, 2026
Time Detected: 03:40 PST
Severity: Critical
Status: Escalated to Tier 2
Attack Technique: Social Engineering


1. Executive Summary

  On February 26, at 03:40AM (PST), a SIEM alert was triggered involving a successfully delivered phishing email to internal user dylan@letsdefend.io, 
  IP 172.16.17.216, promoting a free Windows update. The sender's domain (windows-update.site) tied to IP 132.232.40.201, was unfamiliar to any known legitimate Windows domain.
  After analysis of the sender's domain on VirusTotal, Lumma Stealer infostealer malware was confirmed as the payload. Log analysis confirmed an outbound connection 
  made from 172.16.17.216 (Dylan) to 132.232.40.201 (windows-update.site) 14 hours after the phishing email was recieved, confirming the payload was interacted with by our internal user. Immediate containment of 
  the affected endpoint was employed. Further log analysis confirmed no other internal user recieved or interacted with the malicious payload. Due to the unauthorized
  access of an internal endpoint, escalation to Tier 2 was rendered necessary for further imapct assessment. 


2. Timeline of Events 

  Time (PST)           Event
  03:40              SIEM alert triggered 
  03:42              Phishing email inspected 
  03:44              VirusTotal analysis of payload
  03:47              Log analysis discovered outbound connection from internal host back to sender 
  03:48              More log analysis confirmed no other affected users
  03:49              Affected endpoint isolated 
  03:50              Escalation to Tier 2


3. Detailed Findings 

  Confirmed IOCs:
  - Unfamiliar Windows domain update@windows-update.site with external IP 132.232.40.201 
  - VirusTotal analysis of payload confirmed Lumma Stealer malware 
  - Outbound connection from internal target back to windows-update.site indicating interaction with the malware 

  Assessment:

  The event was classified a successful phishing attack, causing malware execution. Log investigation confirmed internal target was the only affected user, endpoint was isolated, 
  however given Lumma Stealer's known capability to exfiltrate browser credentials and session cookies, full session invalidation and credential reset across all corporate accounts is strongly recommended.


4. Impact Assessment

  Confidentiality: Compromised - access to an internal user's credentials were gained and potential lateral movement or privilege escalation could have been made
  Integrity: Compromised - with successful access to an internal user, the user's data or session could be tampered with
  Availibility: Potential impact - pending further investigation
  Risk: Critical - attacker gained access, likely able to maintain persistence 


5. Recommended Actions

  Immediate: 

  - full session invalidation and credential reset across all corporate accounts
  - Block the identified malicious source IP 
  - Monitor network for any further connections to 132.232.40.201


